{{Infobox heraldry
|image        = Coat of arms of Canada.svg
|alt text     = Coat of Arms of Canada
|caption      = Official depiction of the [[Arms of Canada]], in use since 1994.
|authority    = Canadian Heraldic Authority
|tradition    = Gallo-British
|officername  = Claire Boudreau
|officertitle = Chief Herald of Canada
}}
'''Canadian heraldry''' is the cultural tradition and style of [[Coat of arms|coats of arms]] and other [[Heraldry|heraldic]] achievements in modern and historic [[Canada]], including national, provincial, and civic arms, [[nobility|noble]] and personal arms, [[ecclesiastical heraldry]], heraldic displays as corporate [[logo]]s, and Canadian [[Blazon|heraldic descriptions]].

Derived mainly from heraldic traditions in [[French heraldry|France]] and the [[Heraldry#Gallo-British heraldry|United Kingdom]], Canadian heraldry also incorporates distinctly [[National symbols of Canada|Canadian symbols]], especially native flora and fauna, references to the [[First Nations]] and other [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|aboriginal]] peoples of Canada, and uniquely Canadian elements such as the [[Canadian pale]], derived from the [[Flag of Canada|Canadian flag]]. A unique system of [[cadency]] is used for daughters inheriting arms, and a special symbol for [[United Empire Loyalist]]s. 

In 1988, governance of both personal and corporate heraldry in Canada was patriated from the heraldic authorities in [[College of Arms|England]] and [[Court of the Lord Lyon|Scotland]] with the formation of the [[Canadian Heraldic Authority]], which now has exclusive jurisdiction over granting awards of arms in Canada. Coats of arms are used throughout Canada by all levels of government, in many cases including royal insignia as a mark of authority, as in the recently granted arms of the House of Commons and the Senate, and of Parliament as a combined body. Use of armorial bearings is not limited to governmental bodies; all citizens of Canada have the right to petition for an award of arms, as do other entities including businesses and religious institutions.

== History ==
{{multiple image
| width     = 100
| image1    = France moderne.svg
| alt1      = Royal Arms of France, three gold fleur-de-lis on a blue background
| caption1  = Royal Arms of France
| image2    = Coat of Arms of Nova Scotia.svg
| alt2      = Coat of Arms of Nova Scotia
| caption2  = Coat of Arms of Nova Scotia
}}
The history of heraldry in Canada began with the raising of the [[Coat of Arms of France|Royal Arms of France]] by French explorer [[Jacques Cartier]] in 1534, when he landed on Canadian soil at what is now known as the [[Gasp<U+00E9> Peninsula]].<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada History">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldry.ca/top_en/top_historyHer.htm|publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada|title=The History of Heraldry in Canada|date=28 April 2004|accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref> From the beginning of the [[History of Canada|settlement]] of Canada until the [[Treaty of Paris (1763)|Treaty of Paris]] in 1763, armorial bearings were largely either brought from France or awarded by the [[List of French monarchs|French crown]]. A notable exception is the [[Coat of Arms of Nova Scotia]], awarded in 1625 by [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] (making it the oldest coat of arms in the Commonwealth outside the United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nslegislature.ca/index.php/about/symbols/coat_of_arms |title=Symbols / Facts / About / The Nova Scotia Legislature |publisher=Province of Nova Scotia |date= |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref>), in use until 1868, when it was replaced by a new achievement.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-COACanada" /> The original was later rediscovered, and replaced the 1868 version in 1929.<ref name="COA-NS">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/ns-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Nova Scotia |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref><ref name="fraserNS">{{cite book|last=Fraser|first=Alistair B|title=The Flags of Canada|date=1998-01-30|chapter=Chapter XVIII, Nova Scotia|url=http://www.fraser.cc/FlagsCan/Provinces/NS.html|accessdate=2010-11-03}}</ref> The present-day [[Coat of Arms of Newfoundland and Labrador]] was granted to a private company shortly after that of Nova Scotia, although it did not enter use as the region's arms until the 1920s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.nf.ca/facts3.html |title=Heraldry and Flags: Newfoundland and Labrador Heritage |publisher=Newfoundland and Labrador Heritage Web Site |date=2010 |author=Churchill, Wendy |coauthors=Dalziel, Alex and Rice, Vanessa |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> The Coat of Arms of the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] was first used in 1671 (although no record of the original grant exists, and it was not registered with the College of Arms in London until 1921<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbc.com/hbcheritage/collections/images/coatofarms/ |title=Hbc Heritage - Corporate Collections - Images - The HBC Coat of Arms |publisher=Hudson's Bay Company |date= |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref>), and has been in continual use with minor cosmetic changes to the official depiction ever since.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2008/07/16/f-hbc-history.html |title=CBC News - Canada - The Hudson's Bay Company |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=2008-07-24 |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref>   

Upon ratification of the Treaty of Paris, the [[The Crown|British Crown]] confirmed the French awards of arms.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada History"/> Between 1763 and 1867, the year of [[Canadian Confederation]], there is little evidence of much heraldic activity.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada History" /> After Confederation, however, heraldry in Canada became more widespread, including grants of arms to the provinces, various educational institutions, municipalities, and individuals.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada History" /> In the immediate post-Confederation period, arms were granted to  [[Coat of Arms of New Brunswick|New Brunswick]],<ref name="COA-NB">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/nb-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - New Brunswick |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> [[Coat of Arms of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia]],<ref name="COA-NS"/>  [[Coat of Arms of Ontario|Ontario]],<ref name="COA-ON">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/on-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Ontario |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> and [[Coat of Arms of Quebec|Quebec]],<ref name="COA-QC">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/qc-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Quebec |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> although not to the country as a whole.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-COACanada" /> In the period between the Treaty of Paris and Confederation, the [[Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom|Arms of the United Kingdom]] had served as the emblem of authority within Canada.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-COACanada" />

From 1763 until 1988, heraldry in Canada was under the authority of the [[College of Arms]] in London and the [[Court of the Lord Lyon]] in [[Edinburgh]]. In the late 1980s, the Queen issued [[Letters patent|Letters Patent]] creating the Canadian Heraldic Authority.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada History" /><ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Creation">{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/heraldry/cha/index_e.asp|title=The Canadian Heraldic Authority|publisher=Canadian Heraldic Authority|date=2005-09-27; updated 2006-06-14|accessdate=2008-11-03|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080223224227/http://www.gg.ca/heraldry/cha/index_e.asp |archivedate = February 23, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref>
{{Clear}}

== Modern heraldry ==
=== Official ===
{{Main|Canadian Heraldic Authority}}
{{quote box|width=150px|''Now know Ye that We, by and with the advice of our Privy Council of Canada, do by these presents authorise and empower Our Governor General of Canada to exercise or provide for the exercise of all power and authorities lawfully belonging to Us as Queen of Canada in respect of the granting of armorial bearings in Canada.''|source=From the Royal Warrant<ref name="Watt1">{{cite journal|last=Watt|first=Robert D.|date=Summer 2004|title=A Bold, Successful National Cultural Experiment|journal=Canadian Monarchist News|publisher=The Monarchist League of Canada}}</ref>|salign=right}}
Before the creation of the Canadian Heraldic Authority, Canadians wishing to obtain a legally granted coat of arms had to apply to one of the two heraldic offices in the [[United Kingdom]]: either the [[College of Arms]] in [[London]] or, if of [[Scottish people|Scottish]] descent, the [[Court of the Lord Lyon]] in [[Edinburgh]].<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Creation"/> This process was quite lengthy<U+2014>and costly. In addition, the [[herald]]s in Britain could sometimes be unfamiliar with Canadian history and symbols.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-granting">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldry.ca/top_en/top_grants.htm |title=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada - Obtaining a Grant of Arms |publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada |date=2005-10-23 |accessdate=2008-11-06}}</ref> In time, many Canadians with an interest in heraldry began calling for an office that would offer armorial bearings designed by and for Canadians.<ref name="Watt1"/>

As early as 1967, plans were reportedly in the works to transfer overview of heraldry from the College of Arms in the UK to Canada.<ref>{{cite book|last=Oxom|first=Harry|coauthors=[[Society of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists of Canada]]|title=SOGC: The First Fifty Years 1944-1994|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1995|page=279|isbn=1850705623|url=http://books.google.com/?id=hg8MThpi_h4C&pg=PA279&dq=canada+heraldry+beddoe}}</ref> The push for a wholly-Canadian heraldic system came largely from the Heraldry Society of Canada (now the [[Royal Heraldry Society of Canada]]<ref>{{cite journal|date=5 July 2003|journal=Canada Gazette|publisher=Government of Canada|location=Ottawa|volume= 137|issue=#27|page=7|url=http://www.gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2003/2003-07-05/html/notice-avis-eng.html#i4|title=Canada Gazette Part 1, Supplementary Letters Patent - Name change}}</ref>) almost from its inception,<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-history">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldry.ca/top_en/top_about.htm |title= About the Royal Heraldry Society of Canada |publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada |date=2008-09-29 |accessdate=2008-11-06}}</ref> though it was not seen as a priority by successive national governments.<ref name="Watt1"/> In 1986, [[Vicki Huntington]], a politician from British Columbia, forwarded a brief written by the Royal Heraldry Society of Canada calling for the creation of the Canadian Heraldic Authority to a staff member in then-[[Secretary of State#Canada|Secretary of State]] [[David Crombie]]'s office.<ref name="Watt1"/> Mr. Crombie had his department organise a meeting in Ottawa the following year, to which many national and international heraldic experts were invited. The meeting concluded with "a strong recommendation to government that an Authority be created."<ref name="Watt1"/>

Two years later, on 4 June 1988, then-[[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[Jeanne Sauv<U+00E9>]] authorised the creation of the Canadian Heraldic Authority, made possible by [[Letters patent|Letters Patent]], signed by the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]] on the advice of her [[Canadian Privy Council]], and presented by [[Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|Prince Edward]].<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Creation"/><ref name="Watt1"/> As a result Canada became the first [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] realm outside the United Kingdom to have its own heraldic authority.<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Creation"/><ref name="Watt1"/> Canada also provides full equality to [[Canadian heraldry#Status of women|women]] in terms of inheriting and transmitting arms.<ref name="Watt1"/> Additionally, all [[armiger]]s within Canada may file for trademark protection of their grant of arms under the Trade-Marks Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gg.ca/document.aspx?id=82 |title=The Governor General of Canada - Additional Information |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date= |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref>

=== State and national ===
{{Main|Arms of Canada}}
{{multiple image
 | width     = 150
 | footer    = Official depictions of the Arms of the Sovereign in Right of Canada
 | image1    = Coat of Arms of Canada (1923).jpg
 | alt1      = The official depiction of the Arms of Canada as it appeared in 1923
 | caption1  = 1923
 | image2    = Coat of Arms of Canada (1957).jpg
 | alt2      = The official depiction of the Arms of Canada as painted in 1957 by Allan Beddoe
 | caption2  = 1957
}}

The Arms of Canada (also known as the Royal Arms of Canada<ref name="MacLeod">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/fr-rf/crnCdn/101-eng.cfm|title=A Crown of Maples - Introduction|last=MacLeod|first=Kevin S|coauthors=Jackson, Dr. D Michael and Monet, Fr. Jacques|year=2008|publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> or the Arms of Her Majesty in Right of Canada<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-COACanada">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldry.ca/misc/coatArmsCanada.htm|title=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada: The Coat of Arms of Canada|date=2007-02-05|publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada|accessdate=2008-10-01}}</ref>) has been, since 1921, the official [[coat of arms]] of the [[Monarchy of Canada|Canadian monarch]], and thus also of Canada. It is derived from the [[Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom]],<ref name="pch1">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/symbl/arm2-eng.cfm |title=The Arms of Canada - Description |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date=2010-04-15 |accessdate=2008-10-24}}</ref> with distinctive Canadian elements&mdash;the maple leaves and the reference to the French Royal Arms in the fourth quarter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/symbl/101/103-eng.cfm#a1|title=Symbols of Canada|year=2008|publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage|accessdate=2009-07-01|page=6}}</ref>&mdash;replacing or added to those derived from the British.<ref name="pch1"/>

The arms are used as a mark of authority<ref name="fraserNAT">{{cite book|last=Fraser|first=Alistair B|title=The Flags of Canada|date=1998-01-30|chapter=Chapter I, Canada's National Symbols|url=http://www.fraser.cc/FlagsCan/Nation/NatSym.html|accessdate=2010-11-03}}</ref> by various government agencies and representatives, including the [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]]<ref name="PMO1">{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/|title=Prime Minister of Canada / Premier ministre du Canada|publisher=Office of the Prime Minister|accessdate=2008-10-01}}</ref> and [[Cabinet of Canada|Cabinet]],<ref name="cab1">{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/cabinet.asp|title=Prime Minister of Canada: The Ministry|publisher=Office of the Prime Minister|accessdate=2008-10-01}}</ref> the [[Speaker of the Canadian House of Commons|Speaker of the House of Commons]],<ref name="speakercom1">{{cite web|url=http://www.parl.gc.ca/information/about/people/House/Speaker/index_e.html|title=The Speaker - House of Commons Canada - Welcome|publisher=Parliament of Canada|accessdate=2008-10-01}}</ref> most [[Court system of Canada#Symbols|courts]] (including the [[Supreme Court of Canada|Supreme Court]]<ref name="sprcourt1">{{cite web|url=http://www.scc-csc.gc.ca/|title=Supreme Court of Canada - Welcome Page | Cour supr<U+00EA>me du Canada - Page de bienvenue|date=2008-09-04|publisher=Supreme Court of Canada|accessdate=2008-10-01}}</ref>), and, formerly, [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]]. It is also present on all denominations of [[Canadian dollar|Canadian paper currency]]<ref name="thestar1">{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com/News/Ideas/article/271165 |title=Time to herald our northern coast? |publisher=The Toronto Star |author=Andrew Chung |date=2007-10-28 |accessdate=2010-10-30}}</ref> (the way the Arms are printed on each bill is a security feature<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bankofcanada.ca/en/banknotes/counterfeit/5_cjs_secur.html |title=Original Canadian Journey series $5 and $10 notes- Bank Note Security Features- Counterfeiting prevention- Bank Notes- Bank of Canada |publisher=Bank of Canada |date= |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref>), and on the cover of [[Canadian passport]]s.<ref name="thestar1"/><ref name="passport1">{{cite web|url=http://www.pptc.gc.ca/pptc/specifications.aspx?lang=eng|title=Passport Canada: Features of the Passport|publisher=Passport Canada|accessdate=2008-10-01}}</ref> Since 1962, a [[Heraldic flag#Banner|banner]] of the arms, [[Defacement (flag)|defaced]] with a variant of the Queen's [[Royal Cypher|cypher]], has formed the [[Queen's Personal Canadian Flag|Royal Standard of Canada]], for use by the sovereign in her capacity as monarch of Canada.<ref name="fraser1">{{cite book|last=Fraser|first=Alistair B|title=The Flags of Canada|date=1998-01-30|chapter=Chapter II, Canada's Head of State|url=http://fraser.cc/FlagsCan/Nation/StateHead.html|accessdate=2008-10-01}}</ref> The personal [[Flag of the Governor General of Canada|flag of the Governor General]] has featured the crest of the arms of Canada on a blue background since 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/symbl/o7-eng.cfm|title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Personal Flags and Standards|publisher=Minister of Public Works and Government Services|accessdate=2008-09-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gg.ca/document.aspx?id=78 |title=The Governor General of Canada - Well-known Canadian Emblems |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date= |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref>

On 15 February 2008, the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] was granted its own heraldic symbol following a request by [[Speaker of the Canadian House of Commons|Commons Speaker]] [[Peter Milliken]] to the Canadian Heraldic Authority.<ref name="speakercom1"/> The new symbol for Parliament is a badge of the escutcheon in the Arms of Canada superimposed on the [[Ceremonial mace|mace]] used by the House of Commons as a symbol of its authority derived from the Crown.<ref name="combadge">{{cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=1246|title=Public Register of Arms- House of Commons|publisher=Governor General of Canada|accessdate=7 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/Sites/LOP/Education/CanSymbols/galleries/parliament/hoc_mace-e.asp|title=Library of Parliament - Canadian symbols at Parliament|accessdate=2010-08-23|publisher=Library of Parliament|date=2008-01}}</ref> The [[Senate of Canada|Senate]] was granted a similar badge on 15 April 2008, using its own mace.<ref name="senbadge">{{cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=1283|title=Public Register of Arms- Senate|publisher=Governor General of Canada|accessdate=2010-10-07}}</ref> Parliament as a whole has been granted the right to use the escutcheon of the Arms of Canada, superimposed over the maces of the Commons and Senate in [[saltire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project-pic.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=1284&ProjectElementID=4487 |title=The Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges of Canada - Heraldry |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date=2004-02-25 |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref>

In June 2008, [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Pat Martin]] introduced a [[Motion (democracy)|motion]] into the [[Canadian House of Commons|House of Commons]] calling on the government to amend the coat of arms to incorporate symbols representing Canada's [[First Nations]], [[Inuit]] and [[M<U+00E9>tis]] peoples.<ref>{{cite news
 | title = Coat of arms ignores aboriginal people, MP says
 | publisher = CBC News
 | date=20 June 2008
 | url =http://www.cbc.ca/canada/manitoba/story/2008/06/20/coat-arms.html
 | accessdate = 2008-06-20}}</ref>

=== Provincial ===
{{Main|List of Canadian provincial and territorial symbols}}

