In much the same way that there is a national coat of arms, each [[Provinces and territories of Canada|province and territory]] possesses its own unique arms;<ref name="CanHeritageMain">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/index-eng.cfm|title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion|publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> Saskatchewan's is known formally as Her Majesty's Arms in Right of Saskatchewan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ops.gov.sk.ca/Default.aspx?DN=f9a022a1-b8e7-4bf7-bda2-c245967f30ab |title=Saskatchewan Coat of Arms - Office of the Provincial Secretary - Government of Saskatchewan |publisher=Ops.gov.sk.ca |date= |accessdate=2008-10-29}}</ref> The year after Confederation, [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Queen Victoria]] issued Royal Warrants assigning arms to Canada's original four provinces: [[Coat of Arms of Quebec|Qu<U+00E9>bec]], [[Coat of Arms of Ontario|Ontario]], [[Coat of Arms of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia]], and [[Coat of Arms of New Brunswick|New Brunswick]].<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-COACanada" />

Each [[:Category:Canadian provincial and territorial coats of arms|provincial coat of arms]] includes specific local symbolism;<ref name="CanHeritageMain" /> most also include symbolism derived from the coats of arms of the United Kingdom, France, or both. Since 1868, each province and territory within Canada has been granted arms through warrants either from the monarch directly or from the [[Governor-General|Governor General]], or has assumed them through other means.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-COACanada" />

Apart from [[Flag of Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland and Labrador]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/nf-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Newfoundland and Labrador |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> each province and territory bears at least some elements from its coat of arms upon its flag. The flags of [[Flag of British Columbia|British Columbia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/bc-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - British Columbia |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> [[Flag of New Brunswick|New Brunswick]],<ref name="COA-NB"/> [[Flag of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia]],<ref name="COA-NS"/> and [[Flag of Prince Edward Island|Prince Edward Island]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/pe-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Prince Edward Island |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> are [[Heraldic flag#Banner|banners]] of the provincial arms, while [[Flag of Alberta|Alberta]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/ab-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Alberta |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> [[Flag of Manitoba|Manitoba]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/mb-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Manitoba |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> [[Flag of Ontario|Ontario]],<ref name="COA-ON"/> [[Flag of Saskatchewan|Saskatchewan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/sk-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Saskatchewan |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> the [[Flag of the Northwest Territories|Northwest Territories]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/nt-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Northwest Territories |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> and the [[Flag of Yukon|Yukon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/yt-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Yukon Territory |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> each have the shield of the local coat of arms on their flags, with other design elements. The [[flag of Nunavut]] uses some elements from its coat of arms along with other symbols and colours.<ref name="Nunavutsymbols">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/atc-ac/nu-eng.cfm |title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Nunavut |publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage |date= |accessdate=2008-10-11}}</ref> The shield of the arms of each province, on a blue background and circled with ten gold maple leaves, the whole surmounted by a crown, forms the main element of the [[Flags of the Lieutenant-Governors of Canada|flag of the Lieutenant-Governor]] of that province. The exceptions are Nova Scotia, which uses the [[Union Flag]] defaced with the shield of Nova Scotia, surrounded by green maple leaves, and Quebec, which uses the shield on a white circle with the provincial motto inscribed below.<ref name="CPSCStandards">{{cite web|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/pgm/ceem-cced/symbl/o7-eng.cfm|title=Ceremonial and Canadian Symbols Promotion - Personal Flags and Standards|publisher=Department of Canadian Heritage|accessdate=2008-09-04}}</ref>

=== Municipal ===
The use of armorial bearings among [[:Category:Canadian municipal coats of arms|Canadian cities]] is inconsistent, because many of them have been assumed and brought into force by local governmental authorities, rather than granted from the Crown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldry.ca/top_en/top_misconceptions.htm|publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada|title=Common Misconceptions|accessdate=2008-08-23}}</ref> Many municipal coats of arms either awarded or confirmed by the Canadian Heraldic Authority may be found within the [[Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges of Canada|Public Register of Arms]], though the online version of the Register is not complete.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/faq_e.asp |title=The Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges of Canada - Heraldry |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date=2007-03-26 |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref>

=== Personal ===

In Canada, every [[Canadian nationality law|citizen]] has the right to petition the Crown for a grant of arms.<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Process">{{cite web|url=http://gg.ca/document.aspx?id=79 |title=The Governor General of Canada - Applying for Armorial Bearings |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date= |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref> Canadians who have been appointed to the [[Order of Canada]] are automatically entitled to receive an award of arms including the [[Arms of Canada#Symbolism|ribbon of the Order]], or should they already be armigerous, to encircle their extant arms with the ribbon.<ref name="OCConstitution">{{cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/honours/nat-ord/oc/oc-con_e.asp |title=The Constitution of the Order of Canada |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date=2009-04-30 |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref> Amongst others, all members of the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|Privy Council]] are entitled to [[Supporters (heraldry)|supporters]] in their arms, as are the Speakers of the House of Commons and the [[Speaker of the Canadian Senate|Senate]], Companions of the Order of Canada, Commanders of the Orders of [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|Military Merit]], [[Order of Merit of the Police Forces|Merit of the Police Forces]], and of the [[Royal Victorian Order]].<ref name="OCConstitution" /><ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-Cadency" />

== Unique Canadian elements and practices ==
=== Aboriginal and First Nations symbolism ===
Due to the history of Canada, heraldry in the country has incorporated aboriginal and [[First Nations]] symbols and elements.<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authorityteach">{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/visitus/pdf/Heraldry-Kit-EN.pdf|page= 20|title=Canadian Heraldic Authority - Teacher's Kit (Heraldry in Canada)|publisher=Canadian Heraldic Authority|accessdate=2008-08-23}}</ref> The [[Coat of Arms of Nunavut]],<ref name="Nunavutsymbols"/> for example, includes elements such as an [[inukshuk]], a [[qulliq]], and an [[igloo]], all of which are references to the [[Inuit]] peoples who live in the area,<ref name="nunavut1">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.nu.ca/en/Flag.aspx|title=Facts about Nunavut|publisher=Government of Nunavut|accessdate=2010-10-30}}</ref><ref name="ggnunavut1">{{cite web|url=http://www.gg.ca/heraldry/emb/02/index_e.asp|title=Creation of the Coat of Arms and Flag of Nunavut|date=2005-12-06 |publisher=Governor-General of Canada|accessdate=2008-10-01|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080616212224/http://www.gg.ca/heraldry/emb/02/index_e.asp |archivedate = June 16, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> while the arms of the Canadian Heraldic Authority include [[raven]]s, a First Nations symbol of creation and transformation.<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Process" />

=== Cadency ===
{{Main|Cadency}}

In most systems of heraldry, each unique coat of arms is restricted to a single person. To differentiate identical arms, a system known as cadency was developed, possibly by [[John Writhe]] in 1500<ref name="ukcollege1">{{cite web|url=http://www.college-of-arms.gov.uk/About/12.htm|title=The Law of Arms: The descent of arms|date=2004-04-10|publisher=College of Arms|accessdate=2008-10-02}}</ref> (though other sources argue that systems of cadency were in use as much as two centuries prior<ref>{{cite web|last=Humphery-Smith|first=Cecil R.|url=http://www.britishancestry.org/articles.php?year=2003&month=8&id=12 |title=Articles |publisher=British Ancestry |date=2003-08-27 |accessdate=2010-10-30}}</ref>) which adds a mark known as a ''brisure'' to the plain coat of arms<ref name="glosscadency">{{cite book|last1=Parker|first1=James|last2=Gough|first2=Henry|title=A Glossary of Terms Used in Heraldry|url=http://www.archive.org/stream/aglossarytermsu08parkgoog#page/n117/mode/1up|accessdate=2010-10-30|year=1894|publisher=James Parker & Co.|location=Oxford and London|page=85}}</ref>. Most nations have cadences defined (either officially or through convention) only for male children who inherit otherwise identical arms; Canada has a unique series of cadences for use by female children who inherit arms. As in other heraldic systems, these cadency marks are not always used,<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-Cadency">{{cite web|url=http://education.heraldry.ca/course_canadian.htm|publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada|title=Heraldry Examination|accessdate=2008-08-30}}</ref> though when they are used, the cadences of the heir (in Canada, the first child, whether male or female, according to strict [[primogeniture]]) are removed once the holder dies and the plain coat of arms is inherited.<ref name="hersocscot">{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldry-scotland.co.uk/beginners.html |title=Beginners Heraldry, The Heraldry Society of Scotland - UK Heraldry |publisher=The Heraldry Society of Scotland |date=2005-04-17 |accessdate=2008-11-06}}</ref>

