=== Charges, ordinaries, and divisions of the field ===
The Canadian [[Pale (heraldry)|pale]], a pale division amounting to half the entire field, derived from the [[Flag of Canada|Canadian flag]], is widely used in Canadian heraldry, while the Canadian [[fess]], a similar horizontal division, has been used once.<ref name="RHSC-def-C">{{cite web|url=http://education.heraldry.ca/dictionary/c/c.htm |title=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada Canadian Heraldic Dictionary: C-index |publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada |date=2008-11-18|accessdate=2010-10-02}}</ref><ref name="heraldry1">{{cite web|author=ICE: Webmaster |url=http://education.heraldry.ca/course_innovations.htm |title=RHSC Heraldry Examination |publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada |date= |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> The term ''<U+00E9>rabl<U+00E9>'', referring to maple leaves, is often used in Canadian arms. For example as a ''tressure <U+00E9>rabl<U+00E9>''<ref name="RHSC-def-T">{{cite web|url=http://education.heraldry.ca/dictionary/t/t.htm |title=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada Canadian Heraldic Dictionary: C-index |publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada |date=2008-11-18|accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> in the arms of the [[Monarchist League of Canada]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://monarchist.ca/en/coat-of-arms |title=League Coat of Arms<U+2014>The Monarchist League of Canada |publisher=The Monarchist League of Canada |date= |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> ''coronets <U+00E9>rabl<U+00E9>'' in the arms of [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project-pic.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=340&ProjectElementID=1164 |title=The Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges of Canada - Heraldry |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date=2004-02-25 |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> and Canada's National History Society,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project-pic.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=1277&ProjectElementID=4241 |title=The Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges of Canada - Heraldry |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date=2004-02-25 |accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> and as a partition much like [[engrailed]] or [[Line (heraldry)#Indented and dancetty|dancetty]].<ref name="heraldry1"/><ref name="RHSC-def-E">{{cite web|url=http://education.heraldry.ca/dictionary/e/e.htm |title=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada Canadian Heraldic Dictionary: C-index |publisher=Royal Heraldry Society of Canada |date=2008-11-18|accessdate=2010-10-31}}</ref> Canadian animals and birds, both real and fantastical, have also been widely used in arms, including the mythical raven-bears in the arms of the Canadian Heraldic Authority.<ref name="heraldry1"/>

=== Status of women ===
In both the English<ref name="ukcollege1"/> and the Scottish<ref name="hersocscot"/> systems of heraldry, from which the Canadian draws many of its practices,<ref name="Watt1"/> a woman does not inherit or transmit arms unless she is an ''[[heraldic heiress]]'',<ref name="currer1">{{cite book|last=Currer-Briggs|first=Noel|title=Worldwide Family History|publisher=Routledge|year=1982|page=211|chapter=Appendix A.|isbn=0710009348|oclc=9780710009340|url=http://books.google.com/?id=mJg9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA211&lpg=PA211&dq=heraldic+heiress|accessdate=2008-11-06}}</ref> that is, a daughter of an armiger who has no sons.  In Canadian heraldry, by contrast, women may inherit arms on an equal basis with their brothers (if any).<ref name="Watt1" />  Women in Canada may also transmit their arms to their heirs, regardless of gender.<ref name="Watt1"/> This system of equality for men and women is a result of provisions in the [[Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]],<ref name="Watt1"/> which guarantee, among other things, freedom from discrimination under the law on the basis of sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charterofrights.ca/en/17_00_01 |title=Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms - Equality Rights |publisher=6074332 Canada Inc., in association with SailorJones Media Inc. |date= |accessdate=2008-11-06}}</ref>

=== United Empire Loyalists ===
{{multiple image
 | width     = 100
 | footer    = The Loyalist coronets
 | image1    = Loyalists civil coronet.svg
 | alt1      = The Loyalist Civil Coronet
 | caption1  = Civil
 | image2    = Loyalists military coronet.svg
 | alt2      = The Loyalist Military Coronet
 | caption2  = Military
}}

Those who are descended from the citizens loyal to the British Crown who fled the United States during and shortly after the [[American Revolution|revolution]] are known in Canada as [[United Empire Loyalist]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=A1ARTA0004796 |title=Loyalists |publisher=Historica Foundation |author=Wilson, Bruce G. |date= |accessdate=2008-11-04}}</ref> and are entitled to the use of special [[coronet]]s within their arms, if arms are granted to them.<ref name="UELAC">{{cite journal|last=Ruch|first=John E., UE Hon.FHSC|date=Fall 1990|title=The Canadian Heraldic Authority and the Loyalists|journal=The Loyalist Gazette|volume= XXVIII|issue= 2|url=http://www.uelac.org/UELAC-history/Cdn-Heraldic-Authority-Gazette-1990.pdf|accessdate=2008-11-04}}</ref> There are two versions of the Loyalist coronet: the civil, which is made up of alternating oak and maple leaves, and the military, made up of maple leaves alternating with crossed swords;<ref name="RHSC-def-C"/> the latter is reserved for use by the families of those who served in the British military during the revolution.<ref name="UELAC"/> Proof of Loyalist heritage must be provided to the Canadian Heraldic Authority before permission is granted to use the coronet in arms.<ref name="Royal Heraldry Society of Canada-Cadency" /> Unlike the common use of coronets in heraldry,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/262552/heraldry/8828/Crowns-and-coronets |title=heraldry :: Crowns and coronets - Britannica Online Encyclopedia |publisher=Britannica Online Encyclopedia |date= 2010|accessdate=2010-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | editor = Chisholm, Hugh | encyclopedia = [[Encyclopedia Britannica]] | title = Heraldry | url = http://www.1911encyclopedia.org/Heraldry | accessdate = 2010-10-31 | edition = 11th edition | year = 1911}}</ref> the Loyalist coronet denotes no rank of nobility or royalty, but instead alludes to ancestral allegiance.<ref name="UELAC"/>

== Obtaining arms ==
{{see also|Canadian Heraldic Authority#Grant process|l1=Grant Process}}

All citizens of Canada, as well as corporate bodies, may petition the Crown for an award of arms.<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Process" /> The process for non-armigerous people to obtain arms is relatively simple. For an individual to obtain a grant of arms, a petition must be sent to the [[Chief Herald of Canada|Chief Herald]], providing a biography, references, and completed application forms. If the grant is approved, the individual then consults with heralds from the Authority to work out the design of their award. Upon completion of this process, the grant documents, in the form of letters patent, are created and provided to the grantee. The entire process is subject to certain fees required by the [[Government of Canada]] to cover costs of research and artwork; the fees are not to purchase the grant of arms. For [[corporation]]s and institutions the process is similar.<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Process" />

Those individuals and institutions who are already armigerous through recognised heraldic authorities worldwide may apply to the Canadian Heraldic Authority to have their arms registered. There is no cost associated with application for registration, and it takes less time, approximately three months,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gg.ca/document.aspx?id=84 |title=The Governor General of Canada - FAQ |publisher=Governor General of Canada |date= |accessdate=2010-10-28}}</ref> than application for a new award of arms, which takes approximately twelve to fourteen months.<ref name="Canadian Heraldic Authority-Process" />

